"              \n              \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn rural Indian agricultural households, direct care costs for households with a disabled were as much as three months’ income, and this does not include other indirect costs of care\n.  \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nA study in Tanzania showed that households with a disabled member have a mean consumption of less than 60% of the average, and include 20% more members than average.  This results in limited household spending power\n. \nAnnex B - Timeline of DFID central interventions on disability&#xa0;2013              PUSS attends the \nHigh Level meeting on Disability and Development at UNGA and presents UK position.\n2013              New DFID announcements on disability – all new schools directly funded by DFID will be accessible for people with disabilities, and on improving statistics on disability.\n2013              DFID secondee placed in Ausaid’s disability policy team (two years).\n2013              DFID renews support to the\n Disability Rights Fund2013              PUSS holds two roundtable consultation events with disability focussed civil society groups and activists (February and July)\n2012              Paper presented to DFID’s \nDisability Policy Committee on disability (September).\n2011               HMG provided progress \nupdate on \nUNCRPD commitments.2011              CSD awarded PPAs to\n Action for Disability and Development\n (ADD) and\n Sightsavers (2011 – 2014).\n2010/11               Education for Children with Disabilities Guidance Note developed and shared with country offices.\n2010/11              DFID Stock Take: DFID’s preparedness to mainstream disability issues prepared by Lorraine Wapling January 2010, finalised 2011. \n2010&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDFID Director General’s meeting with Disabled People’s Organisations (DPOs).\n2009&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDFID renews support to the \nDisability Rights Fund \n2010&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDFID Director General’s meeting with Disabled People’s Organisations. 2009              \n‘\nHow to Note’ on Gender and Social Exclusion Analysis developed\n,\n incl\nuding\n disability. \n2009&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nLorraine Wapling, Disability and Development specialist, seconded to the Equity and Rights team.\n2008&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \n‘How to Note’ on Disability \ninclusion \nfinalised and shared with country offices.\n2005&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSocial Exclusion Policy paper finalised, after consultation with disability groups.\n2000              \nDisability Issues paper developed, with support from BOND Disability Group. \n&#xa0;\n15\n&#xa0;\n \nWorld Report on Disability\n.  Geneva/Washington, DC:  WHO/World Bank.  Also \nGroce,N, M. Kett, R. Lang and J-F.Trani\n (2011)\n Third World Quarterly, Vol.32(8): 1493-1513\n.However much of the evidence base for these complex relationships between disability and poverty remain ill-defined and under-researched.  Groce et al conducted a review employing systematic methods (though not a systematic review) of peer-reviewed literature of disability and poverty. Of 293 articles identified in the search, only 27 (9.3%) were found to be evidence-based.  \n \nW\norld Health Organisation\n/W\norld Bank (2011)\n \nWorld Report on Disability\n \n(Washington) \nand also \nGroce,N, M. Kett, R. Lang and J-F.Trani\n (2011)\n Third World Quarterly, Vol.32(8): 1493-1513\n.  \n \nhttp://www.who.int/disabilities/world_report/2011/en/index.html\n \n \nhttp://www.unicef.org/sowc2013/\n \n E.g. \nUN Partnership to Promote the Rights of Persons with Disabilities\n (UNPRPD\n) http://mptf.undp.org/factsheet/fund/RPD00\n \n, and WHO systematic reviews.\n \nEducation for All: The Cost of Accessibility, Steinfeld, Edward, 2005.\n \nDisability in Conditional Cash Transfer Programs: Drawing on Experience in LAC, Mont, Daniel 2006 \nGSDRC\n \nMeasuring Welfare for Small but Vulnerable Groups Poverty and Disability in Uganda, J G Hoogeveen, World Bank Social Protection Discussion Paper 2004\n&#xa0;\n Groce,N, M. Kett, R. Lang and J-F.Trani\n (2011) Third World Quarterly, Vol.32(8): 1493-1513\n \nB Harriss-White, ‘\nPoverty and disability with special reference to rural South India’\n, paper presented at the ‘Staying Poor: Chronic Poverty and Development Policy’ conference, University of Manchester, 7–9 April 2003, at http://idpm.man.ac.uk/cprc/Conference/conferencepapers/HarrissWhite.pdf, accessed 27 July 2010.\n \nA Elwan\n (1999)\n \nPoverty and Disability: A Background Paper for the World Development Report,\n Washington,\n \nDC: World Bank.\n"